package loudest.rajasthantourism;

import android.support.v7.app.AppCompatActivity;
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.widget.TextView;

public class Beauty extends AppCompatActivity {

    public TextView tv_beauty;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_beauty);

        tv_beauty = (TextView)findViewById(R.id.tv_beauty);

        tv_beauty.setText("Art, Craft & Clothes\n" +
                "\n" +
                "In terms of arts and crafts, Rajasthan is among the richest States in India. Artistic creativity dates back to 2nd and 1st centuries, which was further sharpened by the later history which is replete with wars. Rajasthan has everything to offer in handicrafts ranging from ivory, lac, glass, brass, silver, stone, clay, leather, wood, gold and textiles. Rajasthan is specially famous for semi-precious stones and handicrafts, and for its traditional and colourful art. The bazaars spill with products and magnificent glow of colours all over. Intricate hand works carved on handicrafts and on the gems and stones. You will find the colours dancing on the textiles and fabrics with silver or gold threads further enriched with variety of silk-threads, beads, gota, zari, zardosi, banarasi, etc. Block prints, tie and dye prints, Bagaru prints, Sanganer prints and Zari embroidery are major export products from Rajasthan. The blue pottery of Jaipur is quite famous. Rajasthani furniture also has intricate carvings and bright colours.\n" +
                "\n" +
                " The popular crafts include:\n" +
                "\n" +
                "Jewellery: Rajasthan jewellery has its rich princely traditional style which includes the styles ofrakhri, bala, bajuband, gajra, gokhru and jod. It is a hub of precious and semi-precious gem stones. Meenakari is the art of enamelling on gold or silver and is done in the raised-field style. Kundan is the art of setting precious stones in gold. Jaipur is a major center for these works.\n" +
                "Textiles: Rajasthan has an attractive range of hand - block prints, tie and dye and embroider centre red fabrics with mirror work. The art of Khari or over printing in gold  and the bandhni or tie & dye works are very popular. Embroidery work is equally rich which is done on  torans, odhnis, shawls, ghagras and blouses. Similarly, rajashthani carpets are renowned world over.\n" +
                "Block-printing: Rajasthan has a long and distinguished traditon of printing with finely carved wooden blocks.\n" +
                "Leatherware: Rajasthan has a long history in leather craft and industry and leather shoes known as jootis or mojdis are made in Jaipur and Jodhpur.\n" +
                "Paintings: The miniature paintings of Rajasthan are renowned the world over.\n" +
                "Marble Carving & Painting: Rajasthan has a treasure of Marble as well as the art to further enrich this stone. Marble from Rajasthan has been used for construction of famous monuments like Taj Mahal. Marble objects range from decorative plates to boxes and animal figures.\n" +
                "Ivory Carving: Favourite of the earstwhile rulers, Rajasthan has its main ivory carving centres at Udaipur, Bharatpur and Jaipur.\n" +
                "Puppets:Kathputlis or wooden puppets are a common and popular form of entertainment in the villages of Rajasthan.\n" +
                "Metalware:The metalware of Rajasthan comprises of artistic, enamelled and engaved silverware and metalware.\n" +
                "Furniture:The furniture of Rajasthan is as rich as its palaces in design and elegance.\n" +
                "Foods & Flavours\n" +
                "\n" +
                "Rajasthan has a rich culinary art & tradition. This land of princes had some of the finest cooks in their palaces. The royal kitchens of Rajasthan and their 'Khansamas' (the royal cooks) raised the preparation of food to the level of a sublime art. Here, people extensively use milk, curd and refined butter (Ghee) in their daily meals. That makes the food filling, delicious and also heavy. In addition to the formal cuisine, the street food is equally popular which includes delicacies like ‘mirchi bada’ and ‘daal baati choorma’. The non-vegetarian food is equally rich with spices and dry fruits. In addition, they have mouth watering sweet dishes including ‘mewa kachori.\n" +
                "\n" +
                "Dance, Music & Sports \n" +
                "\n" +
                "Rajasthan is famous worldwide for its enthralling dances and music. These dances, music and art forms have been cultivated and patronized by the erstwhile royal courts. Equally rich and fascinating is its folk culture which comes from villages.  The inspiration for the folk dances and the music comes from nature, as well as the day-to-day relationships and chores, more often focused around fetching water from wells or ponds. Folk music is a vital part of Rajasthani culture. Kathputali, Bhopa, Chang, Teratali, Ghindar, Kachchhighori, Tejaji and parth dance  are the examples of the traditional Rajasthani culture. Folk songs are commonly ballads which relate heroic deeds and love stories; and religious or devotional songs known as bhajans and banis (often accompanied by musical instruments like dholak, sitar, sarangi etc.) are also sung.\n" +
                "\n" +
                "The Thar Desert of Rajasthan becomes alive when its dancers take the stage. Rajasthan has a great variety of dances, which are mostly expressions of celebration and festivity. These dancers in colourful costumes have made Thar the most colourful desert in the world. In addition,  each region has its own form of dance styles and performances. Among these, the Ghoomar dance from Udaipur and Kalbeliya dance of Jaisalmer have gained international recognition. They have other forms too including Gair Ghoomar, Raika, Jhoria, Chari Dance, Fire Dance, Drum Dance and many others. Tribals have their own folk dances, songs and music instruments which are vigorous and yet graceful. The local Instruments of Rajasthan include satara, nad, sarangi, kamaycha and morchang.  \n" +
                "\n" +
                "In addition to a camel caravan or camel safari in the Thar deserts,the terrain in Rajasthan is tailor-made for many other adventure sports.You may choose from a number of options which include: Relax with golf,go vintage,or practice archery, go boating or go up in the air over heritage cities by small aircrafts or in hot air balloons. Heights of the Aravalli and Vindhaya hills,the open desert tracts, the vast lakes and rivers,the wildlife parks and little villages make Rajsthan a very exciting exploration.");
    }
}
